===Etymology===
{{m|en|noodnik}} is attested since 1925, {{m|en||nudnik}} since 1929. From {{etyl|yi|en}} {{term|נודניק|tr=nudnik|lang=yi}} < root of {{term|נודיען||to bore|tr=nudyen|lang=yi}} + {{term|־ניק||noun-forming suffix|tr=-nik|lang=yi}}. Ultimately from {{etyl|sla-pro|en}} {{m|sla-pro|*nuda}} < {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*neuti-||need}} < {{m|ine-pro|*nau-||death, to be exhausted}}.

Compare Russian {{term|нудный||tedious|tr=núdnyj|lang=ru}}, Ukrainian {{term|нудний||tedious|tr=núdnýj|lang=uk}}, Polish {{term|nudny||boring|lang=pl}}, Old Church Slavonic {{term|ноудити||tr=nuditi|lang=cu}} or {{term|нѫдити||to compell|tr=nǫditi|lang=cu}}, Hebrew {{term|נוּדְנִיק||[[nag#Verb|nag]]|lang=he}} and English {{term|-nik|lang=en}}.[[Category:English words suffixed with -nik]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

